its enzyme activity","Accelerates enzyme degradation","Stimulates enzyme secretion"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECatecholamines modulate tyrosine hydroxylase activity via negative feedback inhibition. Catecholamines \u003Cstrong\u003Einhibit enzyme activity\u003C/strong\u003E of tyrosine hydroxylase, reducing the rate of conversion of tyrosine to DOPA. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases enzyme expression\u003C/strong\u003E - High catecholamine levels decrease rather than increase enzyme production\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhances substrate binding\u003C/strong\u003E - Catecholamines actually reduce substrate binding as part of their inhibitory effect\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAccelerates enzyme degradation\u003C/strong\u003E - Catecholamines work through direct inhibition rather than increasing enzyme breakdown\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulates enzyme secretion\u003C/strong\u003E - Tyrosine hydroxylase is not secreted; it remains within the cell\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Catecholamines provide negative feedback inhibition on tyrosine hydroxylase activity","Tyrosine hydroxylase is the rate-limiting enzyme in catecholamine synthesis","End-product inhibition helps maintain appropriate catecholamine levels"],"references":["Daubner SC, Le T, Wang S. Tyrosine hydroxylase and regulation of dopamine synthesis. Arch Biochem Biophys. 2011;508(1):1-12. doi:10.1016/j.abb.2010.12.017","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Fillenz M. Regulation of catecholamine synthesis: Multiple mechanisms and th